  "asset": null,
  "timeframe": null,
  "market_context": "The market was in an uptrend with a prior strong impulsive move upward, followed by a compact pullback forming a bull flag. The analyst compared two flags, favoring the one preceded by stronger momentum candles.",
  "key_observation": "The best bull flag is not the textbook zigzag one, but the simpler straight-line pullback—because the preceding impulsive move showed strong momentum (large candles), making it higher probability.",
  "analysis_steps": [
    "Step 1: Identify a strong impulsive move upward (characterized by large, strong candles) as the flagpole.",
    "Step 2: Locate the subsequent pullback against the trend, noting whether it forms a tight consolidation (small candles) — even if it's a simple straight-line drop without lower highs/lows.",
    "Step 3: Evaluate the quality of the flag by comparing the strength of the prior impulsive move across candidate patterns; prefer flags preceded by high-momentum candles.",
    "Step 4: Enter on the breakout candle that closes above the upper trendline of the flag, ideally a strong green candle.",
    "Step 5: Place stop loss just below the lowest point of the flag to allow minor retests without premature exit.",
    "Step 6: Set target using either 2:1 risk-reward or by measuring the flagpole height and projecting it from the breakout point."
  ],
  "outcome": null,
  "lessons": "Flag quality depends more on the strength of the preceding impulsive move than on the flag’s internal structure; simple linear pullbacks can be superior to complex zigzags if momentum is strong.",
